SIMPLE: phlegm
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Phlegm
<hw>Phlegm</hw> <pr>(fl⟦ecr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>phlegme</ets>, <ets>flegme</ets>, L. <ets>phlegma</ets>, fr. Gr.
<grk>fle`gma</grk> a flame, inflammation, phlegm, a morbid, clammy humor
in the body, fr. <grk>fle`gein</grk> to burn. Cf. <er>Phlox</er>,
<er>Flagrant</er>, <er>Flame</er>, <er>Bleak</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and
<er>Fluminate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of the four humors of
which the ancients supposed the blood to be composed. See
<er>Humor</er>.</def> <rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>Viscid mucus secreted in
abnormal quantity in the respiratory and digestive passages.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Old Chem.)</fld> <def>A watery distilled liquor, in
distinction from a spirituous liquor.</def> <rj><au>Crabb.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Sluggishness of temperament; dullness; want of
interest; indifference; coldness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They judge with fury, but they write with <qex>phlegm</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Phlegmagogue</ent>⟦br⟧
